The defendant Dylan James Treviranus was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
AND ARRAIGNMENT 9:35 AM Defendant Dylan James Treviranus in court, in custody. Attorney Lance Morgan Nelsen in court for Dylan James Treviranus.  Attorney Peter James Marvin Kruger in court for State of Wisconsin. State recites agreement that defendant to plead to sole count. For count 1, 1 year jail imposed and stayed for 3 years of probation. Conditions of probation include $50 fine plus costs, 45 days conditional jail with credit for 45 days, pay restitution in amount of $2,441 and comply with all programming as deemed necessary by the DOC. State has complied with Victim's Rights. Defendant pleads no contest. Attorney Nelsen stipulates to a factual basis. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been freely, voluntarily and intelligently made. The Defendant understands all the rights he is waiving by his plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is entered. Defendant makes statement to the Court. 

Court orders 1 year jail imposed and stayed for 3 years of probation. Conditions of probation include $50 fine plus costs, 45 days conditional jail with credit for 45 days, pay restitution in amount of $2,441 and comply with all programming as deemed necessary by the DOC.
